# Code Review Checklist

## VS Code Extension API

- Disposables returned by `vscode.*` APIs must be tracked and disposed (push to a `disposables` array or use `context.subscriptions`).
- Never call `vscode.window.*` or `vscode.commands.*` without checking for cancellation in long-running flows.
- TreeDataProvider changes must fire `onDidChangeTreeData` — verify the correct overload (single node vs full refresh).
- Respect `CancellationToken` in all async operations — check `token.isCancellationRequested` before expensive work.

## Async & Process Safety

- External process calls (`dotnet test`, `dotnet build`) must be cancellable and have timeout handling.
- Temp files/directories created during test runs must be cleaned up in a `finally` block (best-effort `fs.rm`).
- Never use `.Result` or `.Wait()` equivalents — always `await`.
- Floating promises must be intentional and documented (e.g., fire-and-forget cleanup with `.catch(() => {})`).

## Test Result Matching

- TRX test names may differ from discovered FQNs in whitespace, parameter formatting, or qualification level — always use `normalizeTestName` for comparisons.
- New matching logic must handle both fully-qualified names and short names (suffix matching via `.endsWith`).
- Dynamic node creation (`addDynamicCaseNode`) is a fallback — verify the primary matching path is attempted first.

## Tree Integrity

- State changes on nodes must call `refreshNode` (not just set `.state`) to trigger UI updates and `propagateStateUp`.
- `clearRunningStates` must be called in `finishRun` to avoid nodes stuck in "running" after cancellation or errors.
- Verify new node types are handled in `getIcon`, `getTooltip`, `collectMethodNodes`, and `getAllMethodNodes`.

## Testing

- Every new public function must have corresponding unit tests.
- Test names follow `functionName_stateUnderTest_expectedBehavior` convention.
- Use AAA pattern (Arrange / Act / Assert) with blank line separators.
- Mock `vscode` APIs via the existing `test/__mocks__/vscode.ts` — never import the real `vscode` module in tests.
